There he always appeared , however , grey headed , laughing , and happy and he never had anything more to tell of the man who could frighten my aunt . 
These Wednesdays were the happiest days of Mr. Dick's life they were far from being the least happy of mine . 
He could cut oranges into such devices as none of us had an idea of . 
He could make a boat out of anything , from a skewer upwards . 
He could turn cramp bones into chessmen fashion Roman chariots from old court cards make spoked wheels out of cotton reels , and bird cages of old wire . 
But he was greatest of all , perhaps , in the articles of string and straw with which we were all persuaded he could do anything that could be done by hands . 
Mr. Dick's renown was not long confined to us . 
, and so became more and more familiar by degrees , until , at last , he would come into the school and wait . 
